1. What is OAuth?
OAuth is commonly used authoization framework that enables websites and web applications to request limited access to a user's account on another application.
OAuth allows users to grant this access without exposing their login credentials to the requesting application.
This means users can fine-tune which data they want to share rather than having to hand over full control of their account to a third party.

2. OAuth grant types
OAuth grant types determines the the exact sequence of steps that are involved in the OAuth process.
The grant type also affects how the client application communicates with the oauth service at each stage, including how the access token itself is sent.
https://oauth.net/2/grant-types/

OAuth Scopes
For any OAuth grant type, the client appication has to specify which data it wants to access and what kind of operation it wants to perform. It does by using the scope parameter of the authorization request it sends to the OAuth service.

